author: Adam Sullivan
title: Football preview: El Dorado
text: Posted Oct. 22, 2015 at 2:48 PM By Adam Sullivan Posted Oct. 22, 2015 at 2:48 PM A win on Friday for one of these teams likely claims a district championship and a spot in the playoffs as that team will advance to 2-0, the loser will fall to 1-1 and be in a must win scenario next week. El Dorado comes into Friday on a winning streak after defeating rival, Circle 32-13 a week ago. The Cats’ have fallen victim to the injury bug of late and hope to be close to 100% this week. Cade Morrow completed nine passes a week ago amounting 174 yards a one touchdown through the air, he also rushed for 107 yards with another touchdown. Running back Kaden Fowler had six carries for 58 yards but found the end-zone twice in the route. Hayden has pretty much dominated everyone in its path this season. The Wildcats lone hiccup came in week two as they fell to Washburn Rural 26-14. A season ago, Hayden reached the state championship game, falling to champion Bishop Miege 42-35, El Dorado knows hanging with Hayden will be a difficult task. “They are one of the best teams in the state,” said El Dorado head coach Jason Nichols. “We will charter a bus and made the trek to Topeka, preparing for their team will be a whole lot harder than getting ready for the trip.” By the numbers: *Teams stats are updated through week 7 Points per game: El Dorado - 12.4, Topeka Hayden - 37.2 Points allowed: El Dorado - 26.7, Topeka Hayden - 19.2 By Adam Sullivan
